Under the Governor's plan, consumers will already have to pay more sales tax on their everyday household items. Increasing the state's beverage tax just adds insult to injury to hard-working West Virginians.

In addition to soft drink industry job loss, an estimated 4,500 jobs dependent on beverage sales were lost in restaurants, grocery stores, convenience stores, movie, theaters and more. This accounts for $86 million in lost wages due to COVID.

The impact of COVID on our industry and our customers will be felt for the months and even years to come. An estimated 200 direct annualized beverage industry jobs have been lost and will not return. This accounts for $11 million in lost wages.

The beverage tax Gov. Justice is proposing places a much larger burden on hardworking West Virginians than it does wealthy families. People living paycheck to paycheck will be hit hardest by this tax.
